Observation Details: Unmistakable species found and photographed by homeowner Russell Stewart this morning. Foraging in row of spruce trees during my visit; Mr. Stewart observed it going to the feeder on his porch and perched in a birch tree earlier today. Woodpecker with all black bill, dark feet and legs, and dark pupil surrounded by pale yellow irides. Black feathering on face surrounds eye and black also at base of bill. Hind crown and upper nape shows a large, distinct red patch. Black on mid-crown extends onto face. Forehead and throat very pale yellow (almost whitish). Entire back, most of wings, and tail black. Some white visible on the folded wing. Rump and upper tail-coverts whitish. Upper breast blackish with ragged streaking onto lower breast and belly. Flanks tinged with pale yellow. Under tail-coverts not seen. Bird was calling when I first arrived. Calls are very familiar to me from living in California and Arizona, and recently heard them while visiting Arizona and southern California this spring.

Lifer!!! Amazing find by Anne Murray and Iris Wong earlier today. Photos and audio to come! 2nd ever for Vancouver and 13th record for BC. Gorgeous male. Red cap from crown down to the back of the nape. White spot just a bit above the base of the bill and on the chin extending to just under the eye on an otherwise black face. Black at the top of the breast above a white belly with fine black streaks. White undertail coverts and black tail. Fully white rump framed by black back and black wings. Seen on both sides of the river at Ladner Harbour, and just as I was leaving also seen in flight with an acorn. When in flight large white patch seen on top and bottom of each wing. Two longest tail feathers extend in a pointed way reminiscent of the way a LEWO's tailfeathers look.

Locality: Fond du Lac State Forest, Barnum US-MN 46.61787, -92.75539
Observation Details: Stakeout. First seen and reported by Russell Stewart at a feeder in his yard. Medium-sized woodpecker with solid black back, nape, forecrown and upper breast. The black nape wraps forward around the head to the sides of the face and completely encompasses the very light-colored eyes.  The upper nape is bright red and extends forward to meet the black forecrown indicating a female.  The rump, undertail coverts, lower chest and abdomen are all white. The white on the lower chest is broken up by black streaking. The forehead is very light yellow and extends downward to the throat. Seen from between 30 and 100 feet as it went back and forth between nearby spruces, a paper birch and a hopper feeder near the house. Photo to be added. Thank you, Russell, for allowing so many of us to view this gorgeous bird!

Unmistakable species found and photographed by homeowner Russell Stewart this morning. Foraging in row of spruce trees during my visit; Mr. Stewart observed it going to the feeder on his porch and perched in a birch tree earlier today. Woodpecker with all black bill, dark feet and legs, and dark pupil surrounded by pale yellow irides. Black feathering on face surrounds eye and black also at base of bill. Hind crown and upper nape shows a large, distinct red patch. Black on mid-crown extends onto face. Forehead and throat very pale yellow (almost whitish). Entire back, most of wings, and tail black. Some white visible on the folded wing. Rump and upper tail-coverts whitish. Upper breast blackish with ragged streaking onto lower breast and belly. Flanks tinged with pale yellow. Under tail-coverts not seen. Bird was calling when I first arrived. Calls are very familiar to me from living in California and Arizona, and recently heard them while visiting Arizona and southern California this spring.

Continuing. First heard from the bathrooms at Kate’s and Johnson’s cove but had trouble locating it. After a while we saw it fly out from close to the entrance and land in the private property to the east where we got some poor photos. After waiting by the fence line and watching sparrows, we looped around the lake and re-found the bird close to the bathrooms again near the north/west part of the camping area. It’s seems to be hanging around that area. Strikingly patterned woodpecker, black with pale patches on the forehead and on sides of the throat, red barely touching the white on the crown (male), pale iris. Intricate “necklace”streaking against a white belly, all black, notched tail with pale rump and broad white patch on the inner part of the flight feathers visible in flight.

Observation Details: Continuing bird.  First saw woodpecker along the east/west side of the paved loop before the first campsite in post oak.  Silent.  Then watched it vault towards the restroom area and out of sight.  Eventually found later by a photographer in the far northwest corner of the park.  Observed it preening and sunning for a bit before it flew west to private property.  Striking black-backed male woodpecker with unique black and white "clown face" with brilliant red crown. Black breast with trailing thin black streaks. White below. Pale eyes. In flight showed white rump and white wing patches.  Good looks.  Photo'd.

Unmistakable species found and photographed by homeowner Russell Stewart this morning. Foraging in row of spruce trees during my visit; Mr. Stewart observed it going to the feeder on his porch and perched in a birch tree earlier today. Woodpecker with all black bill, dark feet and legs, and dark pupil surrounded by pale yellow irides. Black feathering on face surrounds eye and black also at base of bill. Hind crown and upper nape shows a large, distinct red patch. Black on mid-crown extends onto face. Forehead and throat very pale yellow (almost whitish). Entire back, most of wings, and tail black. Some white visible on the folded wing. Rump and upper tail-coverts whitish. Upper breast blackish with ragged streaking onto lower breast and belly. Flanks tinged with pale yellow. Under tail-coverts not seen. Bird was calling when I first arrived. Calls are very familiar to me from living in California and Arizona, and recently heard them while visiting Arizona and southern California this spring.
Found by Russell Stewart on 02JUL2022. Thank you for letting the birding community get to see this beautiful, rare bird! Very nice meeting you both!!

Locality: Fond du Lac State Forest, Barnum US-MN 46.61787, -92.75539
Observation Details: Stakeout. First seen and reported by Russell Stewart at a feeder in his yard. Medium-sized woodpecker with solid black back, nape, forecrown and upper breast. The black nape wraps forward around the head to the sides of the face and completely encompasses the very light-colored eyes.  The upper nape is bright red and extends forward to meet the black forecrown indicating a female.  The rump, undertail coverts, lower chest and abdomen are all white. The white on the lower chest is broken up by black streaking. The forehead is very light yellow and extends downward to the throat. Seen from between 30 and 100 feet as it went back and forth between nearby spruces, a paper birch and a hopper feeder near the house. Photo to be added. Thank you, Russell, for allowing so many of us to view this gorgeous bird!

Cont species! Bird. Re-seen for me, predominantly on the South side of the river. Red cap from crown down to the back of the nape. White spot just a bit above the base of the bill and on the chin extending to just under the eye on an otherwise black face. Black at the top of the breast above a white belly with fine black streaks. White undertail coverts and black tail. Fully white rump framed by black back and black wings. When in flight large white patch seen on top and bottom of each wing. Seen actively competing with CASJs for acorns. Photos to be added, including photo of the woodpecker actually carrying an acorn.

Observation Details: Continuing bird first seen by Russell Stewart, black body with white patches on the wings and head with a creamy yellow/white area covering lores all the way to the throat. Eye was a pale whiteish color too which occurs in no other woodpeckers that I know of. Red peaked crown in the back of the head and black crisp stripes streaming down the breast. Bathing in a puddle upon arrival and then hopped up to a tree and then the pole followed by another tree. Photos!!!

Very cooperative female Acorn Woodpecker initially reported by homeowner Russell Stewart.  Mostly low on the trunks of the line of spruce trees at the end of the driveway.  Medium sized woodpecker with white/yellow eye and white face separated from the red crown by black.  White breast with black streaks, black back and wings, white wing patches.  Swoopy flight across the road and would return to the same line of trees within a few minutes.  Easy to see from the road by parking before the property and walking to the driveway.  Thank you Russell for sharing your find!

Locality: Ocean Beach--seawatch across from Oceanside Water Polution Plant
Media notes: Tucked away on the ground between rocks after it crash-landed.
Observation Details: A rather odd occurrence, after Ken departed, was a migrant ACORN WOODPECKER that literally blew in off of the ocean around 9 AM and crash-landed on the ground just below the edge of the bluff above the beach, about 15-20' from where I was standing.  It was apparently stunned and remained tucked-in between rocks and on the dirt slope near a path to the beach for about 20 minutes, during which time I took some photos from where I was standing and directed a couple of surfers away from it as they headed down to the beach. Eventually it flushed as another surfer approached, but it flew OK for about 50' and landed on a scrubby dune in the middle of the closed parking lot.  I looked for it on the way back to my car but it had apparently moved on.

Locality: North Sabino Canyon Road, Mount Lemmon, Arizona, US

Observation Details: Unmistakable, with "clown" face pattern, black breast with black streaks extending toward belly, black above with obvious white wing patches in flight. A female by the black band separating red crown from white forehead. I first saw the bird at about 8:10 AM, from Lake Park as it was perched in a tree between Harold Dr and Wesley Dr. and followed it as it flew north and ended up in two oaks at the corner of Keystone Dr and Putnam Dr. There were several California Scrub-Jays visiting those oaks and at least one of the trees had many green acorns in it. At about 8:55 AM the woodpecker was back in trees between Harold Dr and Wesley Dr near Lake Park. At 9:35 AM, just as I was leaving the park, the bird flew off toward the southeast and out of sight. Heard it give "karrrit" and "karrrit-cut" calls several times but no "waka" calls. A favorite species—great to see here!

Slightly smaller than a nearby Northern Flicker, bold, dark (appears glossy-jade in the sun) woodpecker with a pale yellow ring from forehead to throat and pale eye. Red crown does not meet yellow forehead, indicative of adult female. White wing patches in flight. We spent much of our morning watching this bird caching acorns in a few key places. Originally found in a dead snag nearest the Dinosaur playground, it seems her main cache during our visit was the tallest bare tree near the corner of the youth fishing pond. We watched her come and go with acorns, fitting them in an opening in the top. We also watched as a Steller’s Jay raided her stash! We followed her flight pattern to find her also stashing acorns in a telephone pole near the administrative building closest to the barn. Large oak in the parking lot nearest the barn had lots of scrub-Jay and Steller’s Jay activity, and she came and went from there as well. See photos.

Media notes: Perched upright as it seemed to recover -- note its eyelids in this photo. Its eyes appeared OK after this photo was taken.
Observation Details: A rather odd occurrence, after Ken departed, was a migrant ACORN WOODPECKER that literally blew in off of the ocean around 9 AM and crash-landed on the ground just below the edge of the bluff above the beach, about 15-20' from where I was standing.  It was apparently stunned and remained tucked-in between rocks and on the dirt slope near a path to the beach for about 20 minutes, during which time I took some photos from where I was standing and directed a couple of surfers away from it as they headed down to the beach. Eventually it flushed as another surfer approached, but it flew OK for about 50' and landed on a scrubby dune in the middle of the closed parking lot.  I looked for it on the way back to my car but it had apparently moved on.
Very likely undercounted.  Seemed to be everywhere.

Medium sized woodpecker with white/yellow eye and white face separated from the red crown by black.  White breast with black streaks, black back and wings, white wing patches.  Swoopy flight across the road and would return to the same line of trees within a few minutes.  Easy to see from the road by parking before the property and walking to the driveway.  Thank you Russell for sharing your find!

Observation Details: I first detected and identified this bird after hearing its distinctive, nasal, raucous "raaaka raaaka raaaka" calls.  When I found it, it was in one of the oak trees in the middle of the park, but later flew to several different areas of the park.  Medium-sized woodpecker with a black back, wings and tail; white rump; a "clown face" with black face, white throat and forehead; bold white eyering; red cap; black chest; and white belly.  In flight, it showed bold white wing patches.  It was very skittish and would go quiet and then fly a considerable distance away if people or dogs got too close.

Observation Details: Two birds perched close together (a pair?)at the top of a Torrey Pine tree above a cork oak tree at the northwest corner of the Lawn Garden. Two medium-sized black and white woodpeckers with clownish face pattern--with white eyes against dark eye patch and nape, and cream forehead and chin. Picture to follow.  The last Acorn Woodpecker seen here in the garden was recorded in June 2006.  A small population of these birds once nested here during the years 1987-2005-6, and represent the only instance of this species colonizing an artificial oak habitat (cork oak). Photos attached, by Jane Mygatt and Cathie Canepa show at least one of the birds is a female. hard to tell from photos whether other is male (ie no black between red crown red and fore-crown yellow-cream.)

Decided to remain in the area, and after some time, caught sight of the distinct male woodpecker flying in to live oak at camp site 13 along the paved loop around 1:25pm. In flight showed white rump and white wing patches.  Observed tending to an apparent granary tree for almost thirty minutes.  Silent the entire time.  I was also able to flag down Sheila and Jo Ann as they were driving out of the park and get them on the bird.  Excellent views.  Photo'd.

Observation Details: Continuing bird. First seen at about 10:30 AM with what looked like an acorn in its bill in snag at 1920 Keystone Ave. A few minutes (or less) later, it left that tree without the nut, so might have stored it in the snag. From there it flew and landed in the snag just south of 1970 Keystone and stayed there for a few minutes, after which I lost track of it (because I was looking at a Cooper's Hawk). At about 10:55 AM, just as I was about to leave the park, I heard a "karrit" call from near Harold Dr, so went over there and the woodpecker was in a snag behind (west of) 1645 Harold. Saw it do one flycatching sally from there before I left. Seeing it in three different snags makes me wonder if this neighborhood is attractive to this bird because of both the oaks with many acorns and the snags.

Observation Details: Essa é uma fêmea de pica-pau-das-bolotas - acorn woodpecker (Melanerpes formicivorus).  Esta ave prepara-se para o inverno de forma muito sui generis. Primeiro, encontra uma árvore morta e começa a fazer buracos para as bolotas (em geral nozes de carvalho). Cada buraco é feito com muito cuidado, porque se o buraco for grande, outras aves podem roubar suas bolotas. No final do verão, o trabalho de "joalharia" do pica-pau termina, nessa época as bolotas amadurecem e tomam seus lugares na árvore. O tronco de uma grande árvore pode conter cerca de 50.000 bolotas, permitindo ao pássaro um inverno satisfatório. Mais informações podem ser encontradas no Google.

Along with a few other birders, we noticed that most of the Acorn Woodpeckers had the typical dark black tail and wing feathers.  A couple, however, had very noticeable amounts of brown on their tail, primary, secondary, tertial and greater covert feathers.  We were all wondering why?  There is no mention of this color pattern in any of the regularly used bird field guide books.  I looked up some research articles regarding molt in Acorn Woodpeckers and found out something interesting -- adult Acorn Woodpeckers typically undergo one complete molt each year, replacing worn feathers with bright black feathers on the back, wings, and tail.  This process may take quite a few months.  Sometimes, however, they can undergo a "suspended molt", where the molt process is interrupted, in which case any feathers not yet replaced (typically the flight feathers and tail) have to wait to be replaced until the next molt the following spring.  As those old feathers become more worn, they change in color from black to brown.  I suspect this is what we were seeing in these individuals -- see the attached photos.

Media notes: HY immature post attack on newly fledged juvenile. Eyes are changing color but yellow not as bright as mature adults. Growing in its mature crown.
Observation Details: I could find a sole juvenile that's fledged. I did not see the adult birds visiting the nesting cavity. Juvenile has bluish irises that give it a wide-eyed look, lighter-colored bill and pale gape and legs. Can look like Winston Churchill. Seen taking short bursts of flight from tree to tree from about 3 feet to 25 feet above ground. It's traveled a couple of hundred feet from its nesting cavity probably through thick trees. Juvenile was being fed by different adults and at one point also vigorously pecked by a HY bird from the first clutch. After being pecked the juvenile froze on the trunk of a tree for about a minute until the HY flew away and a hummingbird stirred it from its torpor. At least one of the HY immatures begged next to the juvenile in an attempt to be fed and the adults chased it off so there's more begging than juveniles. 6 birds most seen at once and I could unduplicate 7 birds. Birds were flying about in a frenzy. Also observed all three immature birds and an adult female caching bright green acorns with caps: the first time I've seen them caching the new crop of acorns. Most action happening in oaks and pines by tennis court.

First county record and northern Olympic Peninsula record on eBird. Dan Waggoner informs me there is a record from this general area 15-20 years ago.   This bird was apparently found in the spring and reported yesterday via a neighbor to Admiralty Audubon Facebook page with a photo. No location details were posted there so I got up early and headed here to try and confirm that the bird was really here and not some other town. I will add detailed location information once we iron out access issues.
